. Hallucination Is a Foundational Risk (Core Value Prop)
Both Gemini and Claude reported "two sinks" on photos that clearly showed one. This isn't a prompt engineering problem you can fully engineer away — it's a known limitation of VLMs on reflective surfaces, mirrors, and ambiguous angles. The structural penalty helps suppress some false positives, but the index contains thousands of incorrect captions you can't see.

Why it matters: The product's core promise is "find rooms with the features you want." If the index confidently claims features that don't exist, trust breaks the first time a user books a hotel expecting double sinks and finds one. Unlike a recommendation engine where bad results are annoying, this can directly cause users to waste money.

There's no feedback loop. Currently there's no mechanism for users to flag incorrect captions, no way to detect degraded results over time, and no re-captioning when models improve.

2. No Booking Integration Breaks the User Journey
Users find a room at 65% match, see a price — and then what? They have to leave, go to Booking.com or the hotel website, hope the same room is available, and re-enter their dates. That is a significant drop-off point.

LiteAPI has full booking endpoints (pre-book, book, retrieve booking). The rates endpoint you're already calling returns offerId on each room rate. A "Book Now" button that uses that offerId is architecturally a small addition but transforms the product from a discovery tool into a complete booking funnel — and that's where monetization lives (LiteAPI pays commission on completed bookings).

3. Index Goes Stale Silently
Hotels renovate rooms, update photos, add room types, close permanently. The current architecture indexes once and never updates. After 6 months, the Paris index will show:

Photos of rooms that no longer exist
Missing photos of new renovations
Hotels that have closed
Outdated pricing context in captions
There's no scheduled re-index, no last-indexed-at check per hotel, and no way to detect drift between the LiteAPI catalog and your index. Search quality degrades invisibly.

4. Match % Confuses Users and Damages Trust
The current 0–100% scale (with 58% being a "good" result) is counterintuitive. Users interpret a percentage as: "what fraction of what I asked for does this have?" A 58% match for "double sinks" sounds like it half-has double sinks. In reality 58% is near the top of the distribution — a good result.

This is a UX framing problem. Either the scale needs recalibrating (e.g., only show results that would display 70%+, scaled so the realistic range reads as 70–100%), or the label should change ("Strong match" / "Good match" / "Partial match" tiers are more honest).

5. Production Infrastructure Is a Single Point of Failure
One Render instance with no redundancy. When it deploys (2–3 min downtime) or crashes, the entire product is down.
No error monitoring. You only know something broke when a user tells you. No Sentry, no alerting.
No search analytics. You can't see what queries are popular, which return zero results, which hotels get clicked vs. ignored. You can't improve what you can't measure.
No rate limiting on /api/vsearch. A single automated client could exhaust your Gemini quota and Supabase connection pool simultaneously.
Supabase storage: room_embeddings alone is already 266MB. You're on a plan with 500MB–8GB depending on tier. Adding London adds another ~280MB. Adding 5 more cities fills the Pro tier.
6. LiteAPI Dependency Is a Single Point of Failure for the Whole Pipeline
Every part of the product depends on LiteAPI:

Photo URLs are hosted on their CDN (if they change, all lightbox images break)
Room names, room IDs, and hotel metadata come from their API
Live pricing comes from their /hotels/rates endpoint
If their API goes down, changes pricing, or deprecates an endpoint, the product stops working
There's also a coverage problem: LiteAPI reports 7,221 Paris hotels but many have no room photos or empty metadata. You don't know what fraction of the "real" Paris hotel market you're actually showing.

7. English-Only Search in French-Dominant Cities
Room names from LiteAPI for Paris hotels are often French: "Chambre Supérieure", "Suite Présidentielle", "Chambre Deluxe avec Vue". Your caption embeddings are in English (Gemini captions in English), but the room_name field in the hybrid embedding text is the raw French string from LiteAPI. This creates a mismatch in the embedding space that reduces matching accuracy for room-type-level queries.

